\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
On the agreement coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and its relationship to guessing models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Jonas Moss 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
orcid{0000-0002-6876-6964}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Department of Data Science and Analytics
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

BI Norwegian Business School
\emph on

\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

jonas.moss@bi.no
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
The measure of agreement called 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 was invented to handle the paradox of kappa, but does it rest on solid
 foundations? Gwet's motivation for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is based on guessing models, and we argue the recently developed knowledge
 coefficient match the motivation far better, with the details narrowing
 it down to the Brennan–Prediger coefficient.
 We argue that the weighted variant of 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

, called 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{2}$
\end_inset

, is inappropriately defined, and provide an alternative.
 In addition, Gwet's estimator of 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is based on an approximation, and will be asymptotically biased.
 But we provide an exact formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\ac$
\end_inset

, whose plugin estimator is consistent for Gwet's original definition.
 Finally, we will generalize the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{AC}_{2}$
\end_inset

 to different classes of guessing models than the rather restrictive class
 considered by Gwet.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The best known measures of agreement are Fleiss' kappa 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Fleiss1971-to"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, along with its cousin Krippendorff's alpha 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Krippendorff2004-gy"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Cohen's kappa 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cohen1960-mp"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 (and its multirater variant Conger's kappa 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Conger1980-yx"
literal "false"

\end_inset

), and the Brennan–Prediger coefficient 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Brennan1981-kf"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 These are chance-corrected measures of agreement, defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\kappa=\frac{p_{a}-p_{ca}}{1-p_{ca}},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}$
\end_inset

 is the probability of agreement (percent agreement) and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\geq p_{ca}\geq0$
\end_inset

 is a measure of chance agreement.
 (In case 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{ca}=1$
\end_inset

, define 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa=0$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the setting of two raters, if the ratings 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1},X_{2}$
\end_inset

 are distributed according to the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, the probability of agreement equals 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}(F)=P_{X\sim F}(X_{1}=X_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 The chance agreement can be defined in several competing ways, but all
 of the classical measures can be formulated as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{ca}=p_{a}(G)=P_{X\sim G}(X_{1}=X_{2}),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $G=G_{1}\times G_{2}$
\end_inset

 is a distribution over 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1},X_{2}$
\end_inset

 that depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 The Fleiss type chance agreement is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{F}=P_{X\sim\overline{F}\times\overline{F}}(X_{1}=X_{2})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{F}(x)=1/2(F_{1}(x)+F_{2}(x)),$
\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{2}$
\end_inset

 being the marginals of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, the Cohen type chance agreement is 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{C}=P_{X\sim F_{1}\times F_{2}}(X_{1}=X_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, the Brennan–Prediger type chance agreement is 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{BP}=C^{-1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 denotes the number of categories an item can be rated into.
 It clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{-1}$
\end_inset

 equals the probability of agreement between two raters sampling independently
 from a uniform distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 elements.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The definitions of chance agreement lead to the three classical measures
 of agreement, Fleiss' kappa, Cohen's kappa, and the Brennan–Prediger coefficien
t.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\kappa_{F}=\frac{p_{a}-p_{F}}{1-p_{F}},\quad\kappa_{C}=\frac{p_{a}-p_{C}}{1-p_{C}},\quad\kappa_{BP}=\frac{p_{a}-C^{-1}}{1-C^{-1}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These coefficients have natural multirater counterparts, see e.g.
 Moss (2023) for details, and the results in this paper are valid for the
 multirater versions as well as the two-rater variants.
 The intuitive definition of Cohen's kappa leads to it having many proponents,
 but also many detractors, prefering Fleiss' kappa instead.
 According to some authors, however, they both suffer from the purpoted
 paradox of kappa 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Feinstein1990-zb"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 To explain this paradox, consider the rating data in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:gwet-example"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The percent agreement is 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}=117/125=0.9440$
\end_inset

 and the Fleiss-type chance agreement is 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{f}=0.9456$
\end_inset

.
 The resulting Fleiss' kappa is 
\begin_inset Formula $(0.9440-0.9456)/(1-0.9456)=-0.0288$
\end_inset

; it is negative despite a high percent agreement.
 Intuitively, the raters agree less than would be expected due to chance
 alone, hence the resulting Fleiss kappa should be negative.
 Still, many authors regard this feature of Fleiss' kappa (and Cohen's kappa)
 as undesireable, even paradoxical.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "p. 33"
key "Gwet2008-nf"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 writes that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

In this example, raters 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are expected to have a high inter-rater reliability.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

