\begin_layout Standard
The simplest solution to the paradox of kappa, when dealing with nominal
 data, is the Brennan–Prediger coefficient.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{BP}=(p_{a}-0.5)/0.5=0.872$
\end_inset

, which is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

very good
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 according to the classification of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Altman1990-ft"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 But the Brennan–Prediger lies in its motivation: Why are we justified in
 defining chance agreement as 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{-1}$
\end_inset

? That the Brennan–Prediger coefficient is an upper bound to the chance-correcte
d agreement under the assumption that the chance agreement is on the form
 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{X\sim G\times G}(X_{1}=X_{2})$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lawlis1972-qa"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is interested, but is hardly a compelling argument to use it.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Brennan1981-kf"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 provides more motivation, but we don't find it very compelling.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will see below that there is a principled reason to use the Brennan–Prediger
 coefficient if we are justified in making certain assumptions about the
 process that generated the agreement data.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Gwet2008-qk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 introduces 
\begin_inset Formula $\ac$
\end_inset

, as a solution to the paradox of kappa, in the context of such a judgement
 process, which we detail below.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Judgment processes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Examples of judgment processes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Maxwell model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "Section 3"
key "Maxwell1977-lf"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 works in the setting of two judges and binary ratings.
 From his Table II one can derive the the joint model for two ratings 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},x_{2}$
\end_inset

 by two judges as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(x_{1},x_{2})=\alpha p(x_{1})1[x_{1}=x_{2}]+(1-\alpha)p(x_{1})p(x_{2}),\label{eq:maxwell joint}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is the marginal distribution of the data.
 Maxwell then shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\Cor(X_{1},X_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Maxwell's joint distribution is the unconditional variant of a guessing
 model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:full guessing model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 with two judges, i.e., a model on the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p(x_{1},x_{2}\mid s,x^{\star}) & =\{s_{1}1[x_{1}=x^{\star}]+(1-s_{1})q_{r}(x_{1})\}\{s_{2}1[x_{2}=x^{\star}]+(1-s_{2})q_{r}(x_{2})\}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

with associated knowledge coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 The guessing model satisfies 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The judges' guessing distributions are equal to the marginal distribution,
 i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}(x)=q_{2}(x)=p(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The true distribution is assumed to be equal to the marginal distribution,
 i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $t(x)=p(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Both judges share the same skill-difficulty parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 It is Bernoulli distributed with success probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=P(s=1)=Es^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 will 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 if the the case is easy to judge (i.e., a textbook case) and 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 otherwise, and the probability of an item being a textbook case is 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Uniform guessing distribution models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Perreault1989-mg"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 discussed an explicit model for the rating process.
 In their terminology, they used 
\begin_inset Formula $R=2$
\end_inset

 raters, a equal and deterministic skill-difficulty parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 for both raters, uniform guessing distributions, and an arbitrary true
 distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $t(x)$
\end_inset

.
 The resulting univariate model is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(x)=st(x)+(1-s)C^{-1}.\label{eq:Perreault--Leigh model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

From this model they derived that 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\sqrt{(p_{a}-1/C)/(1-1/C)}$
\end_inset

, the square root of the Brennan–Prediger coefficient.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The bivariate distribution of the Perreualt–Leigh model is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
p(x_{1},x_{2}\mid s) & = & s^{2}t(x_{1})1[x_{1}=x_{2}]+(1-s)^{2}C^{-2}+s(1-s)C^{-1}[t(x_{1})+t(x_{2})].\label{eq:Perreault-Leigh}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

The Perreault–Leigh model is strongly related to model used by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Gwet2008-qk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 in his motivation of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ac$
\end_inset

.
 The only modification is that he allows for different skill-difficulty
 parameters for both raters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Marginal guessing distribution models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we have two raters who both guess according to the marginal distribution.
 Their probability of knowing the correct classification is random and equal
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{2}$
\end_inset

, which may be dependent (as in the Maxwell model) or independent (as in
 the Perreault–Leigh model).
 Such models have been proposed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Van_Oest2019-pm"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Grove1981-wb"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the marginal distribution of the ratings, the marginal guessing distribution
 model can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(x_{1},x_{2})=\nu t(x_{1})1[x_{1}=x_{2}]+(1-\nu)ff^{T},\label{eq:marginal guessing distribution}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=E(S_{1}S_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 This model easier to work with than the uniform guessing model for two
 reasons.
 First, it is not hard to verify that in fact 
\begin_inset Formula $f=t$
\end_inset

, giving us a simple estimator of both 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in the marginal distribution (Moss, 2023).
 Second, we do not need to estimate the individual skill-difficulty parameters
 as it can be described solely in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

.
 This is particularily handy when designing tests for the model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Guessing models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The joint distribution of the 
\emph on
guessing model
\emph default
 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(x\mid s,x^{\star})=\prod_{r=1}^{R}\left[s_{r}1[x_{r}=x^{\star}]+(1-s_{r})q_{r}(x_{r})\right].\label{eq:full guessing model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $x_{r}$
\end_inset

 is the rating given by the 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

th judge on an item.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $s=\{s_{1},s_{2},\ldots,s_{r}\}$
\end_inset

 are the 
\emph on
skill-difficulty parameters
\emph default
, the probabilities that the 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

th judge knows the correct classification of an item.
 The skill-difficulty parameters can be deterministic or random.
 For instance, they can be sampled from a Beta distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\star}$
\end_inset

 is the true classification the item, an unknown latent variable.
 These are assumed to be independent of the skill-difficulty parameters
 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 The distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\star}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $t(x^{\star})$
\end_inset

, the 
\emph on
true rating distribution
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $q_{r}(x)$
\end_inset

 are the 
\emph on
guessing distributions
\emph default
, the distributions the ratings are drawn from when the 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

th judge does not know the true classification of the item.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have introduced the guessing model in order to define the notion of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

agreement due to knowledge
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in a precise way.
 To gain an intuition about what we're getting at, first consider the case
 of two judges with potentially different, but deterministic, skill-difficulty
 parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The probability that two judges agree on the classification of an item
 because they both know its classification is the product of their skill
 parameters, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=s_{1}s_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

agree on classification of an item because they both know its classification
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is cumbersome to read, we will call it 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

knowledgeable agreement
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

agree knowledgeably
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 from now.
 Extending this notion to 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 judges, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=\binom{R}{2}^{-1}\sum_{r_{1}>r_{2}}s_{r_{1}}s_{r_{2}}$
\end_inset

 is the probability that a randomly selected pair of judges will agree knowledge
ably on a pair of ratings.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another simple case happens when there are 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 judges with random skill-difficulty parameters that do not wary across
 judges when the item is fixed, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}=S_{2}=\cdots=S_{R}$
\end_inset

, where we use capital letters to emphasize that the 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{r}$
\end_inset

 are random.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $E(S_{r}^{2})$
\end_inset

 is the probability of knowledgeable agreement.
 Finally, in the general guessing model, we find that the probability of
 knowledgeable agreement among two judges is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nu=\binom{R}{2}^{-1}\sum_{r_{1}>r_{2}}E[S_{r_{1}}S_{r_{2}}].\label{eq:knowledgable agreement}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Knowledge coefficient theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main result concerning knowledge coefficients is Theorem 2 of Moss (2023).
 Under suitable assumptions, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 equals classical agreement coefficients or variants of them.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 equals the Brennan–Prediger coefficient if all guessing distributions are
 uniform, and the weighted Fleiss' kappa or Cohen's kappa if all guessing
 distributions are marginal.
 Theorem 2 is summarized in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
