\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size footnotesize
\begin_inset Formula $^{*}$
\end_inset

These three conditions are equivalent, see (i) of Theorem 2 of Moss (2023).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The knowledge coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=\binom{R}{2}^{-1}\sum_{r_{1}>r_{2}}E[S_{r_{1}}S_{r_{2}}]$
\end_inset

 is easy to interpret.
 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{r_{i}}$
\end_inset

 is the probability that judge 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 known the correct classification of an item.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $E[S_{r_{1}}S_{r_{2}}]$
\end_inset

 is the expected probability that both rater 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 and rater 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

 knows the correct classification of an item; it is the probability that
 two items are being rated the same because both raters know the correct
 classification.
 Finally, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 is the probability that two randomly selected raters will knowledgably
 agree on a classification.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a guessing model, we can naturally decompose the probability of chance
 agreement into two parts.
 Knowledgable agreement, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

, and agreement where at least one rater guesses, or 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{g}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p_{a}=\nu+p_{g}\label{eq:agreement decomposition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, in the Perreault–Leigh model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Perreault-Leigh"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, simple calculations demonstrate that the probability of agreement can
 be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}=\nu+C^{-1}(1-\nu)$
\end_inset

, thus the probability of agreement due to guessing is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{-1}(1-\nu)$
\end_inset

.
 Of course, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{g}=\nu-p_{a}$
\end_inset

, which is useful if we want to calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{g}$
\end_inset

 from the better known quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:On-model-assumptions"

\end_inset

On model assumptions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For us, the most important consequence of Theorem 2 is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=\kappa_{BP}$
\end_inset

 when every rater's guessing distribution is uniform.
 This is true for both random and deterministic skill-difficulty parameters
 and for all true rating distributions.
 The
\emph on
 only
\emph default
 crucial assumption is the uniformity of the guessing distribution.
 This assumption has compelling arguments.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "p. 130"
key "Gwet2014-iu"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 states 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
Some authors (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Grove1981-wb"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 among others) have suggested that under the assumption of random rating,
 it may be inappropriate to assign equal probability [
\begin_inset Formula $C^{-1}$
\end_inset

] to all categories.
 Some of these authors even recommended using the observed marginal probabilitie
s.
 I do not recommend this.
 My view on this issue is that if a rater believes that one category is
 more likely than the others to be the correct one, then that category must
 be selected and the rating process should not even be considered random
 at all.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A reasonable counter-argument would be that raters are reasonably aware
 of the true distribution, and are likely to guess according to it.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Van_Oest2019-pm"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 states
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
Raters are motivated to do the coding well and they use the notion that
 an item’s correct category is more likely a large category, with large
 [marginal probability], than a small one.
 Raters may already have some initial ideas about the category proportions
 or they may remember previous outcomes during the coding process and use
 availability heuristics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Tversky1974-yv"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
None of these authors consider the possibility of testing these assumptions
 though.
 Constructing general tests for guessing models is beyond the scope of this
 paper, but, as it turns out, the Perreault–Leigh and marginal guessing
 models are easy to construct tests for.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{F}$
\end_inset

 be the standard empirical estimator of the probability matrix (i.e., the
 agreement matrix divided by 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, the number of items).
 The idea is to use the 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 test 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "Chapter 13"
key "Devore2012-rh"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 to test the nullhypothesis that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{F}$
\end_inset

 is generated from a Perreault–Leigh model or marginal guessing distribution
 model.
 To do this, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{G}$
\end_inset

 be an estimator of the model-implied probability matrix.
 We can estimate this in an ad-hoc manner or using a minimum chi square
 estimator 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Berkson1980-um"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, see the appendix for details.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The resulting test statistic is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T=n\sum_{i=1}^{C}\sum_{j=1}^{C}\frac{\left(\hat{F}_{ij}-\hat{G}_{ij}\right)^{2}}{\hat{G}_{ij}},\label{eq:chisq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

-distributed with 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{2}-C-2$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The distribution of the resulting test statistic when the true distribution
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $[0.2,0.1,0.1,0.3,0.1]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $s=0.7$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n=100$
\end_inset

 is shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:perreault-leigh-figure"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 along with the density of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

-distribution with 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{2}-C-2$
\end_inset

.
 The fit is not amazing, but is decent enough for our purposes.
\end_layout

