\begin_layout Section
Concluding remarks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are many alternatives to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ac$
\end_inset

.
 If you buy the rationale behind the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ac$
\end_inset

, we have argued that knowledge coefficients should be prefered in its stead.
 The Brennan–Prediger coefficient is especially attractive.
 It closely matches Gwet's rationale behind the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ac$
\end_inset

, it is paradox-resistant, and it is more robust than the other easily estimable
 knowledge coefficients discussed in Moss (2023).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another option is to use classical measures of chance-corrected agreement.
 The paradox of kappa is arguably not a paradox at all.
 For why would you expect two raters agreeing less than expected by chance
 to have a positive agreement measure? Just reporting Fleiss' kappa or Cohen's
 kappa is reasonable: Both have a clear interpretation, and they do not
 depend on guessing models for their justification.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have not considered inference for the new weighted definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ac$
\end_inset

 when the guessing models are equal.
 This would involve an application of the delta method of slightly higher
 complexity than the other problems, as we would require the covariance
 between 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}_{wa}$
\end_inset

.
 This covariance can be deduced using the theory of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistics, but is not readily available in the literature to my knowledge.
 Weighted inference under the marginal guessing distribution is easier,
 however, as the knowledge coefficient is invariant with respect to weight
 changes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "subsec:On-model-assumptions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 we provided tests for the validity of the marginal guessing distribution
 model and the Perreault–Leigh model.
 But these only hold for two raters, and we have not considered more general
 models than these, such as the fully uniform guessing distribution model.
 It would be nice to have powerful tests for all model assumptions in the
 coefficient table available.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we restrict ourselves to guessing models, direct estimation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 could also be of interest.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Aickin1990-nj"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Klauer1996-jd"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 both proposed maximum likelihood estimation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 under quite restrictive assumptions (see Moss (2023) for a description
 of their models in the language of guessing models), but these assumptions
 could be loosened.
 The nature of guessing models make pairwise maximum likelihood estimation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Varin2011-nv"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 seem promising.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we saw in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:On-model-assumptions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 there exists data that is not plausibly generated by the marginal guessing
 distribution model or the uniform guessing distribution model.
 If we want to use quantities such as the knowledge coefficient or the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ac$
\end_inset

 in these cases, we might have to go beyond guessing models.
 One possibility is to go in the parametric direction, making explicit models
 for the judgement process that does not separate judgements into a knowledgable
 part and a guessing part.
 Another option is to adopt the notion of credences 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Pettigrew2019-li"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 from philosophy, but there are reasons to believe this would be untenable
 unless the raters are asked for (and trained to) provide classification
 probabilitie, i.e., probabilistic prediction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Gneiting2014-bc"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, instead of doing direct classifications.
\end_layout

