\begin_layout Subsection*
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 tests 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:tests"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the Perreault–Leigh model we rewrite 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Perreault-Leigh"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F=s^{2}\diag(t)+(1-s)11^{T}C^{-2}+s(1-s)(t1^{T}+1^{T}t),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is the true distribution.
 We estimate all 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 parameters simultaneously with 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

-minimization 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Berkson1980-um"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 using the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{constrOptim}$
\end_inset

 function in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{R}$
\end_inset

.
 This approach can be extended to the case of uniform guessing models with
 deterministic 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the marginal guessing distribution model we use formula 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:marginal guessing distribution"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and optimize the 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 statistic with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 using the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{R}$
\end_inset

 function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{optim}$
\end_inset

.
 We fed it the original, estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{f}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The appropriate degree of freedom in a 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 test for a square contingency table varies according to problem and estimation
 method, but is often equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{2}-p-1$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is the number of rows in the contingency table and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is the number of estimated parameters 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "Chapter 13"
key "Devore2012-rh"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In our case 
\begin_inset Formula $p=C$
\end_inset

, as we estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 skill parameter or 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 knowledge coefficient and 
\begin_inset Formula $C-1$
\end_inset

 parameters in the marginal distribution.
 Still, 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{2}-C-2$
\end_inset

 worked best.
 We verified the appropriate degrees of freedom using simulations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Covariance between 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\nu}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:covariance"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Observe that all 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\nu}$
\end_inset

s in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:coefficients"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 are functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{wa}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{wf}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{wc}$
\end_inset

.
 Denote the covariance matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}_{wa},\hat{p}_{wf}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}_{wc}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{y}(x,y,z)=\left[\begin{array}{c}
x\\
\frac{x-y}{1-y}
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

The gradient of this vector is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Cov\left(\hat{p}_{a},\frac{\hat{p}_{a}-\hat{p}_{wc}}{1-\hat{p}_{wc}}\right)=
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.) Brennan–Prediger.
 The
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\nu}{1-p_{a}+\nu}=\frac{p_{a}-p_{c}}{(p_{a}-2)p_{c}+1}
\]

\end_inset


